  <div class="post-content"><p>In a notable shift, a recent agreement has marked a major departure from the Internal Revenue Service long-standing approach of encouraging undocumented immigrants and other migrants to file their taxes.</p><h2>What Changed?</h2><p>While the IRS has historically maintained that all individuals earning income in the U.S. regardless of immigration status are required and encouraged to comply with federal tax laws, the new agreement suggests a significant change in policy direction.</p><h2>What Does This Mean for the Latino Community?</h2><p>If you or someone you know is undocumented and has been filing taxes using an ITIN, it is important to stay informed. We strongly recommend consulting with a tax professional before making any decisions.</p><h2>Our Recommendation</h2><p>At Guzman Tax Accounting, we have extensive experience working with undocumented clients. We can help you understand your options, your rights, and the safest path forward for your specific situation.</p><a href="/consulta-gratuita" class="btn btn-primary" style="margin-top:8px;">Consulta Confidencial Gratis</a></div>
